shared space for communication in a deeply divided nation that seemed destined for civil war along racial lines. At a time when it was illegal to publish images of Nelson Mandela, Bill Cosby became the most recognizable Black man in the country, and, Krabill argues, his presence in the living rooms of white South Africans helped lay the groundwork for Mandela’s release and ascension to power. Weaving together South Africa’s political history and a social history of television, Krabill challenges conventional understandings of globalization, offering up new insights into the relationship between politics and the media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aApartheidzSouth Africa. 0aMass media and race relationszSouth AfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision and politicszSouth AfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszSouth AfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision viewerszSouth AfricaxAttitudesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWhite peoplezSouth AfricaxAttitudesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amedia studies, apartheid, communication, south africa, the cosby show, race, racism, segregation, television, entertainment, tv, medium, racial lines, politics, political sciences, nelson mandela, social history, historical context, globalization, programming, influence, 20th century, attitudes, perspectives, perceptions, huxtables, institutional, authoritarian, authoritarianism, government rule, baasskap, division.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022645188640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226451909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226451909/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Bac